Thanks for the feedback! If your issue is related to the Flutter framework itself,
please open an issue at
[github.com/flutter/flutter](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/new).

## Steps to Reproduce

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39891083/106553664-c7e0f880-6554-11eb-9517-4f10708fcb88.png)

I am using flutter in China, and I must access dart pub through http proxy, but the flutter intellij plugin does not support the use of idea proxy settings.
When I start android-studio by adding the http_proxy environment variable, flutter_intellij uses the proxy correctly, but I cannot debug and run the flutter app.

###### Use Http Proxy
```
set http_proxy=http://127.0.0.1:7890 & set https_proxy=http://127.0.0.1:7890
"C:\Program Files\Android\Android Studio\bin\studio64.exe"
```
Starting DevTools will load normally, but:
```
[        ] Waiting for observatory port to be available...
[+3036 ms] Observatory URL on device: http://127.0.0.1:37729/Emoi_L7U-s8=/
[        ] executing: C:\Users\me\AppData\Local\Android\Sdk\platform-tools\adb.exe -s emulator-5554 forward tcp:0 tcp:37729

[        ] This was attempt #1. Will retry in 0:00:00.100000.
[  +12 ms] E/DartVM  (30122): vm-service: Error: Unhandled exception:
[        ] E/DartVM  (30122): WebSocketException: Invalid WebSocket upgrade request
[        ] E/DartVM  (30122): 
[        ] E/flutter (30122): [ERROR:flutter/runtime/dart_isolate.cc(1137)] Unhandled exception:
[        ] E/flutter (30122): WebSocketException: Invalid WebSocket upgrade request
[ +109 ms] Fail to connect to service protocol: http://127.0.0.1:11498/Emoi_L7U-s8=/: HttpException: Connection closed before full header was received, uri = http://127.0.0.1:11498/Emoi_L7U-s8=/ws
Activating Dart DevTools...
[{"event":"app.progress","params":{"appId":"14233403-292e-4903-8e05-627f62656f86","id":"2","progressId":null,"message":"Activating Dart DevTools...","finished":false}}]
[{"event":"app.progress","params":{"appId":"14233403-292e-4903-8e05-627f62656f86","id":"2","progressId":null,"finished":true}}]
[+9085 ms] Error connecting to the service protocol: failed to connect to http://127.0.0.1:11498/Emoi_L7U-s8=/
```
If use http_proxy environment variable,flutter run will Will be damaged.

### I think the best solution

flutter-intellij should read the proxy settings of the idea and attach it to the runtime environment when executing any `flutter pub.`

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39891083/106554894-50f92f00-6557-11eb-98c1-cc48c8c7496f.png)

If execute flutter run, should not use a proxy.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39891083/106555023-b3eac600-6557-11eb-9c10-32c283f44c4d.png)

I was getting this too and I don't use a proxy.

It looks like it was caused by the issue linked in #5230 

To fix it, I needed to:

1. `flutter channel dev`
2. Download a previous version of this pacakge: `https://plugins.jetbrains.com/files/9212/107560/flutter-intellij.zip?updateId=107560&pluginId=9212&family=INTELLIJ`
3. Install the package by going to `Extensions` and select `Install from Disk`
4. Activate the old version of devtools: `flutter pub global activate devtools 0.9.6+3`
5. In intellij go to `File > Invalidate Caches and Restart`

Another symptom I encountered was the autocomplete not working anymore. It wasn't until step 5 above that the autocomplete finally started working.

Hope that helps you. I was losing my freakin' mind over this...

@xkeyC thanks for this report. I have a few clarifying questions:
1. I don't really understand how this http_proxy variable is supposed to work, as we don't refer to this within the plugin. Is this where you are expecting DevTools to run?
2. Is IntelliJ proceeding beyond the 'Starting DevTools' message before 30 seconds (30 sec is the automatic timeout)? If so, this would mean that DevTools is starting. But it sounds like this only works if you don't use http_proxy?
3. The error message you pasted about observatory - is this from the plugin after running your app has started? And is this when you don't use http_proxy?

1. I hope flutter-intellij can read the proxy settings of idea/android-studio, and set http_proxy for dart when running flutter pub get, flutter pub upgrade, DevTools and other pub commands. (Just like gradle)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/39891083/106643016-11b4f780-65c4-11eb-9914-a6b131408d6d.png)

2. If i use http_proxy, Dart DevTools will be initialized successfully (just like used outside mainland China),Then, the flutter app failed to run.

3. If I do not use http_proxy, the flutter app will start normally, but the dart DevTools will time out and will not work, and every time I press the run button, the "Starting DevTools" pops up.

In other words, if I use http_proxy, then I will not be able to start flutter app. If I don’t use http_proxy, then I will not be able to use dart DevTools.

I think there are two solutions:

1. flutter-intellij set the http_proxy environment variable at runtime for some operations.

2. dart pub adds a new http_proxy option, which can be a configuration file (like gradle) or a command line parameter (dart pub get --http_proxy="xxx" --https_proxy="xxxx"), if it is a configuration file , It will be edited by the user. If it is a command line parameter, it should be set by flutter-intellij.

Thanks for clarifying; I'm looking into how this works further. Are you able to set http_proxy and run your application through the command line? i.e. if you use `flutter run`, does this start the app and DevTools successfully?

@xkeyC We're not planning to build support for this in IntelliJ, but I'm hoping we can figure out a workaround for you and gather some information so we understood your use case better. 

The first issue is we're not familiar with how the HTTP proxy URL works, but I'm gathering this is similar to what's described [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Proxy_servers_and_tunneling)? Essentially, the URL `http://127.0.0.1:7890` is not the location of pub itself, but this is the proxy through which you access the normal pub.dev site and any other address. Is that correct?

Regarding `PUB_HOSTED_URL`, I understand that you can't set this to a URL that is fully up to date with master, but would it work for your purposes to stay on flutter master, but set `PUB_HOSTED_URL` to one of the trailing mirror sites? This way DevTools could be started (potentially with a slightly earlier version, but may be the same), but you won't have the problem of the VM service URL being inaccessible through a proxy URL.

I'm also curious why you're using flutter master instead of one of the better supported channels. Do you have a use case where dev/beta/stable flutter does not suffice?

> Regarding PUB_HOSTED_URL, I understand that you can't set this to a URL that is fully up to date with master, but would it work for your purposes to stay on flutter master, but set PUB_HOSTED_URL to one of the trailing mirror sites? This way DevTools could be started (potentially with a slightly earlier version, but may be the same), but you won't have the problem of the VM service URL being inaccessible through a proxy URL.

Sometimes, Chinese pub mirro can't compile the master channel's flutter.

So, Http_Proxy is the only way I can use the Master channel.

If i use a relatively new package, the Maven mirro in China may have the problem of update delay. I think Http_Proxy is the best solution.

Gradle, maven....they all have good HTTP proxy support. Why don't dart pub do it?

@xkeyC interesting, so the pub mirror site does not only provide the DevTools package, it also compiles the local version of flutter you are running? 

I'm going to close this issue since we're not going to be making changes to the plugin to accommodate this case (although we are looking into app startup changes so it will not hang on DevTools starting). I recommend potentially posting to flutter/flutter with suggestions on how HTTP_PROXY or PUB_HOSTED_URL could be changed for this case; someone there may also have better recommendations for workarounds.
